# TypeScript Conventions

**Official Docs** - [TypeScript Handbook](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/intro.html)

## Type Definitions

Use `type` aliases for all type definitions. Use `interface` only for declaration merging (e.g. extending third-party library types).

```ts
// BAD
interface UserInfo {
  name: string;
  role: 'admin' | 'guest';
}

// GOOD
type UserInfo = {
  name: string;
  role: 'admin' | 'guest';
};
```

Use generic syntax for array types.

```ts
// BAD
const items: string[] = ['a', 'b'];
const readonlyItems: readonly string[] = ['a', 'b'];

// GOOD
const items: Array<string> = ['a', 'b'];
const readonlyItems: ReadonlyArray<string> = ['a', 'b'];
```

## Type Inference

Only add explicit type annotations when they narrow the type. Do not annotate when TypeScript already infers the correct narrow type.

```ts
// BAD - redundant annotation
const name: string = 'admin';
const [isActive, setIsActive] = useState<boolean>(false);

// GOOD - inference is sufficient
const name = 'admin'; // inferred as literal 'admin'
const [isActive, setIsActive] = useState(false);

// GOOD - annotation narrows a wide inference
const employees = new Map<string, number>();
type UserRole = 'admin' | 'guest';
const [role, setRole] = useState<UserRole>('admin');
```

## Immutability

Mark object properties as `readonly` by default. Omit `readonly` only when mutation is genuinely needed.

```ts
// BAD
type User = {
  id: string;
  name: string;
};

// GOOD
type User = {
  readonly id: string;
  readonly name: string;
};
```

Use `ReadonlyArray<T>` for arrays that must not be mutated. When processing data, return new arrays/objects instead of mutating in place.

```ts
// BAD - mutates input
function removeFirst(users: Array<User>): Array<User> {
  users.splice(0, 1);
  return users;
}

// GOOD - returns new array
function removeFirst(users: ReadonlyArray<User>): ReadonlyArray<User> {
  return users.slice(1);
}
```

## Const Assertions

Declare constants with `as const` for literal narrowing and immutability.

```ts
// BAD
const LOCATION = { x: 50, y: 130 }; // { x: number; y: number }
LOCATION.x = 10; // allowed

// GOOD
const LOCATION = { x: 50, y: 130 } as const; // { readonly x: 50; readonly y: 130 }
```

When a predefined type exists, combine `as const satisfies` for both validation and narrowing.

```ts
type OrderStatus = {
  pending: 'pending' | 'idle';
  fulfilled: boolean;
  error: string;
};

// BAD - mutable, wide type
const IDLE_ORDER: OrderStatus = { pending: 'idle', fulfilled: true, error: '' };

// GOOD - immutable, validated, narrowed
const IDLE_ORDER = {
  pending: 'idle',
  fulfilled: true,
  error: '',
} as const satisfies OrderStatus;
```

## Enums

Do not introduce new enums. Retain existing enums in the codebase.

Use literal types when you only need the type. Use `as const` arrays when you need to iterate. Use `as const` objects when mapping arbitrary key-value pairs.

```ts
// BAD
enum UserRole {
  GUEST = 'guest',
  MODERATOR = 'moderator',
  ADMIN = 'administrator',
}

// GOOD - literal type
type UserRole = 'guest' | 'moderator' | 'administrator';

// GOOD - iterable const array
const USER_ROLES = ['guest', 'moderator', 'administrator'] as const;
type UserRole = (typeof USER_ROLES)[number];

// GOOD - key-value mapping
const COLORS = {
  primary: '#B33930',
  secondary: '#113A5C',
} as const;
type ColorKey = keyof typeof COLORS;
type ColorValue = (typeof COLORS)[ColorKey];
```

## Required vs Optional Properties

Keep the majority of properties required. Use optional properties sparingly.

When a property can be absent but you want callers to explicitly acknowledge it, prefer `T | undefined` over `?`. This forces the caller to pass the key, preventing silent omission bugs.

```ts
// BAD - easy to forget passing userId
type AuthOptions = {
  userId?: string;
};

// GOOD - caller must explicitly pass userId (even if undefined)
type AuthOptions = {
  readonly userId: string | undefined;
};
```

## Discriminated Unions

Use discriminated unions to model data that can be in distinct shapes. This eliminates "bags of optionals" and enables exhaustiveness checking.

```ts
// BAD - allows impossible states
type FetchState<TData> = {
  status: 'idle' | 'loading' | 'success' | 'error';
  data?: TData;
  error?: Error;
};

// GOOD - each state carries exactly its required data
type FetchState<TData> =
  | { status: 'loading' }
  | { status: 'success'; data: TData }
  | { status: 'error'; error: Error };
```

Handle discriminated unions with `switch` and ensure exhaustiveness.

```ts
function render(state: FetchState<User>): string {
  switch (state.status) {
    case 'loading':
      return 'Loading...';
    case 'success':
      return state.data.name;
    case 'error':
      return state.error.message;
  }
}
```

## Template Literal Types

Use template literal types to enforce valid string patterns instead of raw `string`.

```ts
// BAD
const version: string = '2.6.1';
const endpoint: string = '/api/users';

// GOOD
type Version = `v${number}.${number}.${number}`;
const version: Version = 'v2.6.1';

type ApiRoute = 'users' | 'posts' | 'comments';
type ApiEndpoint = `/api/${ApiRoute}`;
const endpoint: ApiEndpoint = '/api/users';
```

## any, unknown, and Assertions

Never use `any`. Use `unknown` for ambiguous data, then narrow before use.

```ts
// BAD
function parse(input: any): number {
  return input;
}

// GOOD
function parse(input: unknown): number {
  if (typeof input !== 'number') {
    throw new Error('Expected a number');
  }
  return input;
}
```

Avoid type assertions (`as T`) and non-null assertions (`!`). Use them only as a last resort with a comment explaining why.

## Suppressing Type Errors

When a TypeScript error truly cannot be fixed, use `@ts-expect-error` (never `@ts-ignore`). Always include a description.

```ts
// BAD
// @ts-ignore
const user = createUser('Gabriel');

// GOOD
// @ts-expect-error: library types incorrectly require number, but string is valid
const user = createUser('Gabriel');
```

## Boolean Flags vs Type Unions

Replace accumulating boolean flags with a single type union when states are mutually exclusive.

```ts
// BAD
const isPending = true;
const isProcessing = false;
const isConfirmed = false;

// GOOD
type Status = 'pending' | 'processing' | 'confirmed' | 'expired';
const status: Status = 'pending';
```

## null vs undefined

- Use `null` to explicitly represent "no value" in assignments and return types.
- Use `undefined` when the value does not exist (e.g. omitted fields in payloads, optional query params).

## Imports

### Type Imports

Always use `import type` for type-only imports. Prefer top-level `import type` over inline `import { type ... }`.

```ts
// BAD - may leave side-effect import after transpilation
import { type User } from './user';

// GOOD
import type { User } from './user';
```

### Named Exports

Use named exports. Avoid default exports unless the framework requires them.

```ts
// BAD
export default function createUser() { ... }

// GOOD
export function createUser() { ... }
```

## Functions

### Declaration Syntax

Use function declarations, not arrow function expressions, for named functions.

```ts
// BAD
const getUser = (id: string): User | undefined => {
  return db.find(id);
};

// GOOD
function getUser(id: string): User | undefined {
  return db.find(id);
}
```

Arrow functions are appropriate for inline callbacks and short expressions passed as arguments.

```ts
// GOOD - inline callback
const activeUsers = users.filter((user) => user.isActive);
```

### Purity and Responsibility

Write functions that are pure, stateless, and have a single responsibility. Accept at least one argument and return data. Avoid side effects.

### Single Object Argument

When a function takes more than one primitive, use a single options object.

```ts
// BAD
transformInput('client', false, 60, 120, null, true, 2000);

// GOOD
transformInput({
  method: 'client',
  isValidated: false,
  minLines: 60,
  maxLines: 120,
  defaultInput: null,
  shouldLog: true,
  timeout: 2000,
});
```

### Return Types

Declare explicit return types on top-level / exported functions. This prevents accidental signature changes and improves readability.

```ts
// BAD - inferred return type may drift
export function getUser(id: string) {
  return db.find(id);
}

// GOOD
export function getUser(id: string): User | undefined {
  return db.find(id);
}
```

For internal/private helpers, inference is acceptable.

### Error Handling - Result Types

Before throwing, consider whether a Result type is more appropriate. Use throwing when the framework expects it (e.g. request handlers). Use Result types when the caller would need a manual try-catch.

```ts
type Result<TValue, TError extends Error = Error> =
  | { ok: true; value: TValue }
  | { ok: false; error: TError };

function parseJson(input: string): Result<unknown> {
  try {
    return { ok: true, value: JSON.parse(input) };
  } catch (error) {
    return { ok: false, error: error as Error };
  }
}

const result = parseJson('{"name": "John"}');
if (result.ok) {
  console.log(result.value);
} else {
  console.error(result.error);
}
```

### Discriminated Function Arguments

When function args have mutually exclusive groups of properties, model them as a discriminated union instead of optional args.

```ts
// BAD
type NotifyParams = {
  data?: Products;
  title?: string;
  time?: number;
  error?: string;
};

// GOOD
type NotifyParams =
  | { status: 'success'; data: Products; title: string }
  | { status: 'loading'; time: number }
  | { status: 'error'; error: string };

function notify(params: NotifyParams): void { ... }
```

## Naming Conventions

| Construct                  | Convention                       | Example                               |
| -------------------------- | -------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Local variables            | camelCase                        | `filteredProducts`                    |
| Booleans                   | `is`/`has`/`should`/`can` prefix | `isDisabled`, `hasAccess`             |
| Constants (primitives)     | UPPER_SNAKE_CASE                 | `MAX_RETRY_COUNT`                     |
| Constants (objects/arrays) | UPPER_SNAKE_CASE + `as const`    | `const IDLE_ORDER = { ... } as const` |
| Functions                  | camelCase                        | `filterByType`                        |
| Types                      | PascalCase                       | `OrderStatus`                         |
| Generic params             | `T` + PascalCase descriptor      | `TRequest`, `TValue`                  |

### Generics

Prefix generic type parameters with `T` followed by a descriptive name. Single-letter generics (`T`, `K`, `U`) are not allowed.

```ts
// BAD
function merge<T, K>(a: T, b: K): T & K {
  return { ...a, ...b };
}

// GOOD
function merge<TBase, TOverride>(a: TBase, b: TOverride): TBase & TOverride {
  return {
    ...a,
    ...b,
  };
}
```

### Acronyms

Treat acronyms as whole words with only the first letter capitalized.

```ts
// BAD
generateUserURL();
const FAQList = [];

// GOOD
generateUserUrl();
const FaqList = [];
```

Avoid abbreviations unless widely understood.

## Comments and JSDoc

Favor expressive code over comments. Comments explain "why", not "what".

```ts
// BAD
// convert to minutes
const m = s * 60;

// GOOD
const SECONDS_IN_MINUTE = 60;
const minutes = seconds * SECONDS_IN_MINUTE;
```

Use JSDoc only when the function's behavior is not self-evident. Be concise. Use `@link` to reference related symbols.

```ts
/**
 * Subtracts two numbers.
 */
function subtract(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a - b;
}

/**
 * Does the opposite of {@link subtract}.
 */
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}
```

Use TSDoc for public APIs, libraries, and configuration types.
